M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Determine whether your SaaS business model is fundamentally viable and capital-efficient. Use this to calculate unit economics, assess profitability, manage cash runway, and decide when to scale vs. o
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|This is not a fin reporting tool—it's a framework for PMs to understand whether the business can sustain growth, when to prioritize efficiency over growth, and which investments have positive returns.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Metrics that measure profitability at the customer level—the foundation of sustainable SaaS.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Gross Margin** — Percentage of revenue remaining after direct costs (COGS).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** A feature that generates $1M revenue at 80% margin is worth far more than $1M at 30% margin. Margin determines which features to prioritize.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `(Revenue - COGS) / Revenue × 100`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **COGS includes:** Hosting, infrastructure, payment processing, customer onboarding costs
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** SaaS 70-85% good; <60% concerning
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**CAC (Customer Acquisition Cost)** — Total cost to acquire one customer.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Shapes entire go-to-market str. Determines which channels are viable and how much you can invest in product-led growth.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `Total Sales & mkt Spend / New Customers Acquired`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Varies by model—Enterprise $10K+ ok; SMB <$500 target
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Include:** mkt spend, sales salaries, tools, commissions
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**LTV (Lifetime Value)** — Total revenue expected from one customer over their lifetime.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Tells you what you can afford to spend on acquisition. Higher LTV enables premium channels and longer payback periods.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula (simple):** `ARPU × Average Customer Lifetime (months)`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula (better):** `ARPU × Gross Margin % / Churn Rate`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula (advanced):** Account for expansion, discount rates, cohort-specific retention
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Must be 3x+ CAC; varies by segment
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**LTV:CAC Ratio** — Efficiency of customer acquisition spending.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Is growth sustainable or are you buying revenue at a loss? Determines when to scale vs. optimize.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `LTV / CAC`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** 3:1 healthy; <1:1 unsustainable; >5:1 might be underinvesting
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Note:** This ratio alone doesn't tell the full story—also need payback period
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Payback Period** — Months to recover CAC from customer revenue.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Cash efficiency. Faster payback = reinvest sooner. Slow payback can kill growth even with good LTV:CAC.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `CAC / (Monthly ARPU × Gross Margin %)`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** <12 months great; 12-18 ok; >24 months concerning
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Critical:** Must have cash to sustain payback period
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Contribution Margin** — Revenue remaining after ALL variable costs (not just COGS).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** True unit profitability. Includes support, processing fees, variable OpEx.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `(Revenue - All Variable Costs) / Revenue × 100`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Variable costs:** COGS + support + payment processing + variable customer success
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** 60-80% good for SaaS; <40% concerning
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Gross Margin Payback** — Payback period using actual profit, not revenue.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** More accurate than simple payback. Shows true cash recovery time.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `CAC / (Monthly ARPU × Gross Margin %)`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Typically 1.5-2x longer than simple revenue payback
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**CAC Payback by Channel** — Compare payback across acquisition channels.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Not all channels are created equal. Optimize channel mix based on payback efficiency.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** Calculate CAC and payback separately for each channel
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Use:** Allocate budget to faster-payback channels when cash-constrained
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Metrics that measure how efficiently you use cash to grow the business.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Burn Rate** — Cash consumed per month.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Determines what you can build and when you need funding. High burn requires aggressive revenue growth.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula (Gross Burn):** `Monthly Cash Spent (all expenses)`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula (Net Burn):** `Monthly Cash Spent - Monthly Revenue`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Net burn <$200K manageable for early stage; >$500K needs clear path to revenue
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Runway** — Months until cash runs out.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Literal survival metric. Dictates timeline for milestones, fundraising, profitability.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `Cash Balance / Monthly Net Burn`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** 12+ months good; 6-12 manageable; <6 months crisis mode
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Rule:** Raise when you have 6-9 months runway, not 3 months
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**OpEx (Operating Expenses)** — Costs to run the business (excluding COGS).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Your team's salaries live here. Where "efficiency" cuts happen during downturns.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Categories:** Sales & mkt (S&M), Research & dev (R&D), General & Administrative (G&A)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Should grow slower than revenue as you scale (operating leverage)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Net Income (Profit Margin)** — Actual profit or loss after all expenses.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** True bottom line. Are you making money? Can you self-fund growth?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `Revenue - All Expenses (COGS + OpEx)`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Early SaaS often negative (growth mode); mature should be 10-20%+ margin
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Working Capital Impact** — Cash timing differences between revenue recognition and cash collection.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Annual contracts paid upfront boost cash. Monthly billing delays cash. Affects runway calculations.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Example:** $1M annual contract paid upfront = $1M cash now, not $83K/month
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Use:** Understand cash vs. revenue timing when planning runway
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Composite metrics that measure growth vs. profitability trade-offs.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Rule of 40** — Growth rate + profit margin should exceed 40%.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Framework for balancing growth vs. efficiency. Guides when to prioritize profitability over growth.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `Revenue Growth Rate % + Profit Margin %`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** >40 healthy; 25-40 acceptable; <25 concerning
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Example:** 60% growth + (-20%) margin = 40 (healthy growth-mode SaaS)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Example:** 20% growth + 25% margin = 45 (healthy mature SaaS)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Magic Number** — Sales & mkt efficiency.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Is your GTM engine working? Should you scale spend or optimize first?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Formula:** `(Current Quarter Revenue - Previous Quarter Revenue) × 4 / Previous Quarter S&M Spend`
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Benchmark:** >0.75 efficient; 0.5-0.75 ok; <0.5 fix before scaling
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Note:** "× 4" annualizes quarterly revenue change
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Operating Leverage** — How revenue growth compares to cost growth.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Are you scaling efficiently? Revenue should grow faster than costs.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Measure:** Revenue growth rate vs. OpEx growth rate over time
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Good:** Revenue growth 50%, OpEx growth 30% (positive leverage)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Bad:** Revenue growth 20%, OpEx growth 40% (negative leverage)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Unit Economics** — General term for profitability of each "unit" (customer, seat, transaction).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Is the business model fundamentally viable at the unit level?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Calculate:** Revenue per unit - Cost per unit
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Requirement:** Positive contribution required; aim for >$0 after all variable costs
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Not vanity metrics:** High LTV means nothing if payback takes 4 years and customers churn at 3 years.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Not static benchmarks:** "Good" CAC varies wildly by business model (PLG vs. enterprise sales).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Not isolated numbers:** LTV:CAC ratio without payback period can mislead (great ratio, terrible cash efficiency).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **Not just fin's problem:** PMs must own unit economics—every feature dec impacts margins and CAC.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Use these when:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Evaluating whether to scale acquisition (LTV:CAC, payback, magic number)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Deciding feature investments (margin impact, contribution to LTV)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Planning runway and fundraising (burn rate, runway, Rule of 40)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Comparing customer segments or channels (unit economics by segment)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Board/investor reporting (Rule of 40, magic number, LTV:CAC)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Choosing between growth and profitability (Rule of 40 trade-offs)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Don't use these when:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Making decisions without revenue ctx (pair with `saas-revenue-growth-metrics`)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Comparing across wildly different business models without normalization
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Early product discovery (pre-revenue focus on PMF, not unit economics)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Short-term tactical decisions (use engagement metrics, not LTV)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Use the templates in `template.md` to calculate your unit economics metrics.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Gross Margin = (Revenue - COGS) / Revenue × 100
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|COGS includes:
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Hosting & infrastructure costs
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Payment processing fees
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Customer onboarding costs
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Direct delivery costs
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Revenue: $1,000,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- COGS: $200,000 (hosting $120K, processing $50K, onboarding $30K)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Gross Margin = ($1M - $200K) / $1M = 80%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is gross margin improving as you scale? (Should benefit from economies of scale)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Which products/features have highest margins? (Prioritize those)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Are margins >70%? (SaaS should be high-margin)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|CAC = Total Sales & mkt Spend / New Customers Acquired
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Include in S&M spend:
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- mkt salaries & tools
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Sales salaries & commissions
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Advertising & paid channels
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- SDR/BDR team costs
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Sales & mkt Spend: $500,000/month
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- New Customers: 100/month
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- CAC = $500,000 / 100 = $5,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is CAC consistent across channels? (Calculate by channel)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is CAC increasing or decreasing over time? (Should decrease with scale)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Does CAC vary by customer segment? (SMB vs. Enterprise)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|LTV (Simple) = ARPU × Average Customer Lifetime (months)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|LTV (Better) = ARPU × Gross Margin % / Monthly Churn Rate
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|LTV (Advanced) = Account for expansion, cohort-specific retention, discount rate
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example (Simple):**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- ARPU: $500/month
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Average Lifetime: 36 months
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- LTV = $500 × 36 = $18,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example (Better):**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- ARPU: $500/month
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Gross Margin: 80%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Monthly Churn: 2%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- LTV = ($500 × 80%) / 2% = $400 / 0.02 = $20,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is LTV growing over time? (From expansion, improved retention)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Does LTV vary by cohort? (Are new customers more/less valuable?)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Does LTV vary by segment? (Enterprise vs. SMB)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|LTV:CAC Ratio = LTV / CAC
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- LTV: $20,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- CAC: $5,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- LTV:CAC = $20,000 / $5,000 = 4:1
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is ratio >3:1? (Minimum for sustainable growth)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is ratio >5:1? (Might be underinvesting in growth)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is ratio improving or degrading over time?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Interpretation:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **<1:1** = Losing money on every customer (unsustainable)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **1-3:1** = Marginal economics (optimize before scaling)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **3-5:1** = Healthy (scale confidently)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **>5:1** = Potentially underinvesting (could grow faster)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Payback Period (months) = CAC / (Monthly ARPU × Gross Margin %)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- CAC: $5,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Monthly ARPU: $500
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Gross Margin: 80%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Payback = $5,000 / ($500 × 80%) = $5,000 / $400 = 12.5 months
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is payback <12 months? (Excellent)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is payback <18 months? (Acceptable)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Do you have cash runway to sustain payback period?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Critical insight:** 4:1 LTV:CAC with 36-month payback is a cash trap. 3:1 LTV:CAC with 8-month payback is better for growth.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Contribution Margin = (Revenue - All Variable Costs) / Revenue × 100
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Variable Costs include:
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- COGS
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Support costs (variable component)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Payment processing
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Variable customer success costs
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Revenue: $1,000,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- COGS: $200,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Variable Support: $50,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Payment Processing: $30,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Contribution Margin = ($1M - $280K) / $1M = 72%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is contribution margin >60%? (Good for SaaS)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Are certain products/segments lower margin? (Consider sunsetting)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Does margin improve with scale?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Gross Burn Rate = Total Monthly Cash Spent
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Net Burn Rate = Total Monthly Cash Spent - Monthly Revenue
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Monthly Expenses: $800,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Monthly Revenue: $400,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Gross Burn: $800,000/month
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Net Burn: $400,000/month
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is net burn decreasing over time? (Path to profitability)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is burn rate sustainable given runway?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- What's the burn rate relative to revenue? (Burn multiple)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Runway (months) = Cash Balance / Monthly Net Burn
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Cash Balance: $6,000,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Net Burn: $400,000/month
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Runway = $6M / $400K = 15 months
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Do you have >12 months runway? (Healthy)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Do you have <6 months runway? (Crisis—raise now or cut burn)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Can you reach next milestone before runway ends?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Rule:** Start fundraising at 6-9 months runway, not 3 months.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|OpEx = Sales & mkt + R&D + General & Administrative
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Track as % of Revenue:
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|S&M as % of Revenue
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|R&D as % of Revenue
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|G&A as % of Revenue
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Revenue: $10M/year
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- S&M: $5M (50% of revenue)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- R&D: $3M (30% of revenue)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- G&A: $1M (10% of revenue)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Total OpEx: $9M (90% of revenue)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Are OpEx categories growing slower than revenue? (Operating leverage)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is S&M spend efficient? (Check magic number)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is G&A <15% of revenue? (Should stay low)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Net Income = Revenue - COGS - OpEx
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Profit Margin % = Net Income / Revenue × 100
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Revenue: $10M
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- COGS: $2M
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- OpEx: $9M
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Net Income = $10M - $2M - $9M = -$1M (loss)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Profit Margin = -10%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is profit margin improving over time? (Path to profitability)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- At current growth rate, when will you break even?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Are you investing losses in growth? (Acceptable if LTV:CAC is healthy)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Rule of 40 = Revenue Growth Rate % + Profit Margin %
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example 1 (Growth Mode):**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Revenue Growth: 80% YoY
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Profit Margin: -30%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Rule of 40 = 80% + (-30%) = 50 ✅ Healthy
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example 2 (Mature):**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Revenue Growth: 25% YoY
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Profit Margin: 20%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Rule of 40 = 25% + 20% = 45 ✅ Healthy
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example 3 (Problem):**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Revenue Growth: 30% YoY
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Profit Margin: -35%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Rule of 40 = 30% + (-35%) = -5 🚨 Unhealthy
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is Rule of 40 >40? (Healthy balance)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is Rule of 40 >25? (Acceptable)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is Rule of 40 <25? (Burning cash without sufficient growth)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Trade-offs:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Early stage: Maximize growth, accept losses (60% growth, -20% margin = 40)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Growth stage: Balance (40% growth, 5% margin = 45)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Mature: Prioritize profitability (20% growth, 25% margin = 45)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Magic Number = (Current Quarter Revenue - Previous Quarter Revenue) × 4 / Previous Quarter S&M Spend
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|```
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Q2 Revenue: $2.5M
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Q1 Revenue: $2.0M
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Q1 S&M Spend: $800K
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Magic Number = ($2.5M - $2.0M) × 4 / $800K = $2M / $800K = 2.5
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is magic number >0.75? (Efficient—scale S&M spend)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is magic number 0.5-0.75? (Acceptable—optimize before scaling)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is magic number <0.5? (Inefficient—fix GTM before spending more)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Interpretation:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **>1.0** = For every $1 in S&M, you get $1+ in new ARR (excellent)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **0.75-1.0** = Efficient, scale confidently
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **0.5-0.75** = Marginal, optimize before scaling
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- **<0.5** = Inefficient, fix before investing more
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|Track over time to see if you're scaling efficiently.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Quarter | Revenue | YoY Growth | OpEx | YoY Growth | Leverage |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics||---------|---------|------------|------|------------|----------|
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Q1 2024 | $8M | - | $6M | - | - |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Q2 2024 | $10M | 25% | $7M | 17% | Positive ✅ |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Q3 2024 | $12M | 20% | $9M | 29% | Negative ⚠️ |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Is revenue growing faster than OpEx? (Positive leverage)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Are you scaling OpEx too fast relative to revenue?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Which OpEx category is growing fastest? (R&D, S&M, G&A)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Unit economics vary dramatically by segment:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Segment | CAC | LTV | LTV:CAC | Payback | Gross Margin |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics||---------|-----|-----|---------|---------|--------------|
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| SMB | $500 | $2,000 | 4:1 | 8 months | 75% |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Mid-Market | $5,000 | $25,000 | 5:1 | 12 months | 80% |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Enterprise | $50,000 | $300,000 | 6:1 | 24 months | 85% |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Which segment has best unit economics?
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Which segment has fastest payback? (Prioritize when cash-constrained)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Which segment has highest LTV? (Invest in retention/expansion)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|See `examples/` folder for detailed scenarios. Mini examples below:
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Company:** CloudAnalytics (mid-market anl SaaS)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Unit Economics:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- CAC: $8,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- LTV: $40,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- LTV:CAC: 5:1 ✅
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Payback Period: 10 months ✅
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Gross Margin: 82% ✅
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Capital Efficiency:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Monthly Net Burn: $300K
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Runway: 18 months ✅
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Rule of 40: 55 (40% growth + 15% margin) ✅
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Magic Number: 0.9 ✅
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Analysis:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Strong unit economics (5:1 LTV:CAC, 10-month payback)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Efficient GTM (0.9 magic number)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Healthy balance (Rule of 40 = 55)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Sufficient runway (18 months)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Action:** Scale acquisition aggressively. Economics support growth.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Company:** EnterpriseCRM (enterprise sales motion)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Unit Economics:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- CAC: $80,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- LTV: $400,000
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- LTV:CAC: 5:1 ✅ (looks great!)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Payback Period: 36 months 🚨 (terrible!)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Gross Margin: 85%
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Capital Efficiency:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Monthly Net Burn: $2M
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Runway: 9 months 🚨
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Average Customer Lifetime: 48 months
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- Average Contract: $100K/year
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Analysis:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- ⚠️ Great LTV:CAC ratio (5:1) masks cash problem
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- 🚨 36-month payback with 9-month runway = cash trap
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- 🚨 Takes 3 years to recover CAC, but only 9 months of cash
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- ⚠️ Customers stay 4 years, so economics work IF you have cash
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Problem:** You'll run out of cash before recovering acquisition costs.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Actions:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|1. Negotiate upfront annual payments (reduce payback to 12 months)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|2. Raise capital to extend runway (need 36+ months to sustain growth)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|3. Reduce CAC (shorten sales cycle, improve conversion)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|4. Target smaller deals with faster payback (mid-market vs. enterprise)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Company:** SocialScheduler (SMB soc media tool)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Quarter-over-Quarter Trend:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Quarter | Revenue | OpEx | Net Income | Revenue Growth | OpEx Growth |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics||---------|---------|------|------------|----------------|-------------|
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Q1 | $1.0M | $800K | -$800K | - | - |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Q2 | $1.3M | $1.2M | -$1.2M | 30% | 50% 🚨 |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|| Q3 | $1.6M | $1.8M | -$1.8M | 23% | 50% 🚨 |
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Analysis:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- 🚨 OpEx growing FASTER than revenue (50% vs. 23-30%)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- 🚨 Losses accelerating ($800K → $1.8M in 2 quarters)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- 🚨 Negative operating leverage (should be positive)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|- ⚠️ Scaling S&M and R&D without corresponding revenue growth
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Problem:** Burning cash faster while revenue growth is slowing.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Actions:**
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|1. Freeze headcount until revenue catches up
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|2. Cut inefficient S&M spend (magic number likely <0.5)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|3. Focus on improving unit economics before scaling
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|4. Aim for OpEx growth <revenue growth
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "Our LTV:CAC is 6:1, amazing!"
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** 6:1 ratio with 48-month payback is a cash trap. You'll run out of money before recovering CAC.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Always pair LTV:CAC with payback period. 3:1 with 10-month payback beats 6:1 with 36-month payback.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "LTV = $100/month × 36 months = $3,600"
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** You're using revenue, not profit. Actual LTV after 30% COGS = $2,520, not $3,600.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Always include gross margin in LTV calculations. `LTV = ARPU × Margin % / Churn Rate`.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "We need to grow faster—let's double S&M spend!" (Magic Number = 0.3)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** You're pouring gas on a broken engine. Doubling spend will just accelerate cash burn without proportional revenue growth.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Only scale S&M when magic number >0.75. If <0.5, fix GTM efficiency first.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "LTV = ARPU × Lifetime" (ignoring expansion, discount rates, cohort variance)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** Overstating LTV for dec-making. Reality: expansion boosts LTV; discounting reduces it; cohorts vary.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Use sophisticated LTV models for big decisions. Simple LTV ok for directional guidance only.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "$10K revenue today = $10K revenue in 5 years"
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** Overstating LTV for long-payback businesses. $10K in 5 years is worth ~$7.8K today (at 5% discount rate).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Discount future cash flows for LTV periods >24 months. Use NPV (net present value).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "Channel A has $5K CAC, Channel B has $8K CAC—Channel A is better!"
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** If Channel A has 24-month payback and Channel B has 8-month payback, Channel B is actually better (faster cash recovery).
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Compare CAC + payback together, not CAC in isolation.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "Rule of 40 = 50, we're crushing it!" (60% growth, -10% margin, burning $5M/month)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** Rule of 40 doesn't account for absolute burn. You might have great balance but only 3 months runway.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Pair Rule of 40 with burn rate and runway. Balance matters, but survival matters more.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "Blended CAC is $2K, blended LTV is $10K, we're good!"
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** SMB segment might have $500 CAC / $2K LTV (great), while Enterprise has $20K CAC / $15K LTV (terrible). Blended metrics hide the problem.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Calculate unit economics by segment. Optimize each independently.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "Gross margin is 80%, our margins are great!"
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** After variable support costs (10%) and payment processing (3%), contribution margin might be 67%—not 80%.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Track both gross margin (COGS only) AND contribution margin (all variable costs). Use contribution margin for unit economics.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Symptom:** "We have 12 months runway based on burn rate" (but all contracts are paid monthly)
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Consequence:** Annual contracts paid upfront boost cash temporarily. Monthly contracts delay cash collection. Runway is longer/shorter than burn rate suggests.
M|saas-economics-efficiency-metrics|**Fix:** Account for working capital when calculating runway. Cash-based runway ≠ revenue-based runway.
